# tl;dr

To multiply text, call `String#repeat`. 

    System.out.println( temp + &quot; : &quot; + &quot;*&quot;.repeat( votes ) );


# `String#repeat` to multiply text

Your call to `+=` *adds* text, but does not *multiply* text.

To multiply, call [`String#repeat`][1] in Java 11+. 

    int votes = 5 ;
    String stars = &quot;*&quot;.repeat( votes ) ;

Result. 

```none
*****
```

## Example app

You did not indicate how you represent your votes-per-temperature. So I created a [`NavigableMap`][2].

For simplicity I used the &quot;enhanced for loop&quot; (for-each). No need to keep an index counter in this case here.

The for-each is based on a [`NavigableSet`][3] of keys drawn from the map, via the call to `NavigableMap#navigableKeySet`. 


```java
package work.basil.example.stars;

import java.util.Map;
import java.util.NavigableMap;
import java.util.TreeMap;

public class App
{
    public static void main ( String[] args )
    {

        NavigableMap &lt; Integer, Integer &gt; temperatureToVotes =
                new TreeMap &lt;&gt;(
                        Map.of(
                                63 , 1 ,
                                65 , 2 ,
                                68 , 5 ,
                                69 , 3 ,
                                70 , 1 ,
                                72 , 3 ,
                                75 , 2
                        )
                );

        for ( Integer temperature : temperatureToVotes.navigableKeySet() )
        {
            Integer votes = temperatureToVotes.get( temperature );
            String message = temperature.toString().concat( &quot; : &quot; ).concat( &quot;*&quot;.repeat( votes ) );
            System.out.println( message );
        }
    }
}
```

